<subSubSection id="818ED2C3FFC4FF9EFF1EFB849A52D894" pageId="5" pageNumber="445" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="C92B8148FFC4FF9EFF1EFB849A52D894" blockId="5.[151,1437,839,2031]" pageId="5" pageNumber="445">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC4FF9EFF1EFB849A18D9C2" bold="true" box="[198,326,1151,1177]" pageId="5" pageNumber="445">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The shape of tergite 6 of male, with posterior margin simple, gently curved (
<figureCitation id="51AF9DCDFFC4FF9EFAD7FB7B9E04D9C1" box="[1295,1370,1152,1178]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–7" captionStartId="6.[151,270,1894,1918]" captionTargetBox="[171,1426,688,1887]" captionTargetId="figure-272@6.[151,1436,683,1893]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 1–7. Swammerdamella spinigera sp. nov. (♂, holotype). 1. Wing, scale bar: 0.5 mm. 2. Spiracular sclerite, scale bar: 0.05 mm. 3. Tergite 6, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 4. Tip of abdomen in lateral view, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 5. Segment 7 (sternite above), scale bar: 0.1 mm. 6. Genital capsule in ventral view, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 7. Sperm pump, scale bar: 0.1 mm." pageId="5" pageNumber="445">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
), not produced posteriorly into a more or less triangular projection, is unique among the European species of 
<taxonomicName id="0E94FACBFFC4FF9EFF4FFB36997AD9BC" authority="Enderlein. The" authorityName="Enderlein. The" box="[151,548,1229,1255]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Swammerdamella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="445" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC4FF9EFF4FFB369A34D9BD" box="[151,362,1229,1254]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="445">Swammerdamella</emphasis>
Enderlein. The
</taxonomicName>
new species is closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="0E94FACBFFC4FF9EFC6EFB369FA4D9BC" authority="(Duda, 1928)" baseAuthorityName="Duda" baseAuthorityYear="1928" box="[950,1274,1229,1255]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Swammerdamella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="445" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pediculata">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC4FF9EFC6EFB369F0DD9BD" box="[950,1107,1229,1254]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="445">S. pediculata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="AD05FCB9FFC4FF9EFBBBFB369FACD9BC" author="Duda, O." box="[1123,1266,1229,1255]" pageId="5" pageNumber="445" pagination="1 - 62" refId="ref5438" refString="Duda, O. (1928) 5. Scatopsidae. In: Lindner, E. (Ed.), Die Fliegen der Palaearktischen Region, 2 (1). Schweizerbart, Stuttgart, pp. 1 - 62." type="book chapter" year="1928">Duda, 1928</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from Central Europe and to the above-mentioned new species from 
<collectingCountry id="B183C1D8FFC4FF9EFCFDFB0F9832D855" box="[805,876,1268,1294]" name="Spain" pageId="5" pageNumber="445">Spain</collectingCountry>
, as may be seen by the long narrow M fork on wing (
<figureCitation id="51AF9DCDFFC4FF9EFF3AFAE19A79D86F" box="[226,295,1306,1332]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–7" captionStartId="6.[151,270,1894,1918]" captionTargetBox="[171,1426,688,1887]" captionTargetId="figure-272@6.[151,1436,683,1893]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 1–7. Swammerdamella spinigera sp. nov. (♂, holotype). 1. Wing, scale bar: 0.5 mm. 2. Spiracular sclerite, scale bar: 0.05 mm. 3. Tergite 6, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 4. Tip of abdomen in lateral view, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 5. Segment 7 (sternite above), scale bar: 0.1 mm. 6. Genital capsule in ventral view, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 7. Sperm pump, scale bar: 0.1 mm." pageId="5" pageNumber="445">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) and the shape of the genital capsule, especially the strongly sclerotized aedeagal plate (
<figureCitation id="51AF9DCDFFC4FF9EFA9CFAE19ED0D86F" box="[1348,1422,1306,1332]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–7" captionStartId="6.[151,270,1894,1918]" captionTargetBox="[171,1426,688,1887]" captionTargetId="figure-272@6.[151,1436,683,1893]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 1–7. Swammerdamella spinigera sp. nov. (♂, holotype). 1. Wing, scale bar: 0.5 mm. 2. Spiracular sclerite, scale bar: 0.05 mm. 3. Tergite 6, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 4. Tip of abdomen in lateral view, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 5. Segment 7 (sternite above), scale bar: 0.1 mm. 6. Genital capsule in ventral view, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 7. Sperm pump, scale bar: 0.1 mm." pageId="5" pageNumber="445">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). The male genital structures (
<figureCitation id="51AF9DCDFFC4FF9EFE2BFABA9963D800" box="[499,573,1345,1371]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–7" captionStartId="6.[151,270,1894,1918]" captionTargetBox="[171,1426,688,1887]" captionTargetId="figure-272@6.[151,1436,683,1893]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 1–7. Swammerdamella spinigera sp. nov. (♂, holotype). 1. Wing, scale bar: 0.5 mm. 2. Spiracular sclerite, scale bar: 0.05 mm. 3. Tergite 6, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 4. Tip of abdomen in lateral view, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 5. Segment 7 (sternite above), scale bar: 0.1 mm. 6. Genital capsule in ventral view, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 7. Sperm pump, scale bar: 0.1 mm." pageId="5" pageNumber="445">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
), with hardly developed lateral projections and posterior lobes densely beset with short spinulae, allow an easy separation from these species. In the female, the poor knowledge of the genital structures of most species of the genus does not allow to give diagnostic characters for 
<taxonomicName id="0E94FACBFFC4FF9EFA5DFA749A58D895" authorityName="Haenni" authorityYear="2009" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Swammerdamella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="445" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinigera">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC4FF9EFA5DFA749A58D895" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="445">S. spinigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="818ED2C3FFC4FF9DFF1EFA209E3BDF55" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="446" pageId="5" pageNumber="445" type="description">
<paragraph id="C92B8148FFC4FF9DFF1EFA209AE1DC17" blockId="5.[151,1437,839,2031]" lastBlockId="6.[151,1436,152,642]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="446" pageId="5" pageNumber="445">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC4FF9EFF1EFA209A00D8AE" bold="true" box="[198,350,1499,1525]" pageId="5" pageNumber="445">Description.</emphasis>
Male. 1.5 mm long (in alcohol). Shining black in general colour, with contrasting yellow tarsi. Head shining black, higher than long; antenna longer than head height, clavate, with 8 flagellomeres, gradually shortening and widening towards apex, the penultimate flagellomere more than twice as broad as long, the last one rounded, about 2.5 times longer than preceding one, nearly as broad as long; palpus large, broadly triangular at base, pointed at apex. Thorax. Notum shining black, with irregularly arranged rather coarse dark pilosity, also present on scutellum; margin of scutellum devoid of setae except basally; pleurae shining, largely devoid of pilosity except on elongate triangular spiracular sclerite (
<figureCitation id="51AF9DCDFFC4FF9EFBB6F93F9FE9DB85" box="[1134,1207,1732,1758]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–7" captionStartId="6.[151,270,1894,1918]" captionTargetBox="[171,1426,688,1887]" captionTargetId="figure-272@6.[151,1436,683,1893]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 1–7. Swammerdamella spinigera sp. nov. (♂, holotype). 1. Wing, scale bar: 0.5 mm. 2. Spiracular sclerite, scale bar: 0.05 mm. 3. Tergite 6, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 4. Tip of abdomen in lateral view, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 5. Segment 7 (sternite above), scale bar: 0.1 mm. 6. Genital capsule in ventral view, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 7. Sperm pump, scale bar: 0.1 mm." pageId="5" pageNumber="445">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Wing (
<figureCitation id="51AF9DCDFFC4FF9EFAC7F93F9E3ADB85" box="[1311,1380,1732,1758]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–7" captionStartId="6.[151,270,1894,1918]" captionTargetBox="[171,1426,688,1887]" captionTargetId="figure-272@6.[151,1436,683,1893]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 1–7. Swammerdamella spinigera sp. nov. (♂, holotype). 1. Wing, scale bar: 0.5 mm. 2. Spiracular sclerite, scale bar: 0.05 mm. 3. Tergite 6, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 4. Tip of abdomen in lateral view, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 5. Segment 7 (sternite above), scale bar: 0.1 mm. 6. Genital capsule in ventral view, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 7. Sperm pump, scale bar: 0.1 mm." pageId="5" pageNumber="445">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) 1.6 mm long, hyaline, membrane entirely covered with dense, minute, light micropilosity; radial veins short, ending in the vicinity of the middle of wing, light brown; 9 dorsal setae on basal portion of R, 5 dorsal setae on R 
<subScript id="5510830DFFC4FF9EFF17F8B39BB7DA0D" attach="left" box="[207,233,1864,1878]" fontSize="6" pageId="5" pageNumber="445">4+5</subScript>
, no dorsal setae on R 
<subScript id="5510830DFFC4FF9EFE30F8B39AAEDA0D" attach="right" box="[488,496,1864,1878]" fontSize="6" pageId="5" pageNumber="445">1</subScript>
; posterior veins translucent; fork of M long and narrow, nearly as long as stem, the branches diverging markedly only near apex of wing. Halter brown, with somewhat lighter brownish stem; legs concolorous with body except tarsi yellow, strongly contrasting; anterior femora with a posteroventral irregular row of elongate setae. Abdomen. Tergites 1–6 shining black, with sparse coarse dark pilosity, denser and longer on posterior tergites; tergite 1 narrow, with a weakly sclerotized median longitudinal line; tergite 6 (
<figureCitation id="51AF9DCDFFC7FF9DFF47FF639BBBDDE9" box="[159,229,152,178]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–7" captionStartId="6.[151,270,1894,1918]" captionTargetBox="[171,1426,688,1887]" captionTargetId="figure-272@6.[151,1436,683,1893]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 1–7. Swammerdamella spinigera sp. nov. (♂, holotype). 1. Wing, scale bar: 0.5 mm. 2. Spiracular sclerite, scale bar: 0.05 mm. 3. Tergite 6, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 4. Tip of abdomen in lateral view, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 5. Segment 7 (sternite above), scale bar: 0.1 mm. 6. Genital capsule in ventral view, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 7. Sperm pump, scale bar: 0.1 mm." pageId="6" pageNumber="446">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
) simple, with posterior margin gently convex; sternites 2–6 present, beset with dark pilosity as tergites; sternite 7 (
<figureCitation id="51AF9DCDFFC7FF9DFECBFF459A06DD83" box="[275,344,190,216]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–7" captionStartId="6.[151,270,1894,1918]" captionTargetBox="[171,1426,688,1887]" captionTargetId="figure-272@6.[151,1436,683,1893]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 1–7. Swammerdamella spinigera sp. nov. (♂, holotype). 1. Wing, scale bar: 0.5 mm. 2. Spiracular sclerite, scale bar: 0.05 mm. 3. Tergite 6, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 4. Tip of abdomen in lateral view, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 5. Segment 7 (sternite above), scale bar: 0.1 mm. 6. Genital capsule in ventral view, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 7. Sperm pump, scale bar: 0.1 mm." pageId="6" pageNumber="446">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
) shining, smooth, with complex posterior margin; tergite 7 (
<figureCitation id="51AF9DCDFFC7FF9DFBC3FF459F3FDD83" box="[1051,1121,190,216]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–7" captionStartId="6.[151,270,1894,1918]" captionTargetBox="[171,1426,688,1887]" captionTargetId="figure-272@6.[151,1436,683,1893]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 1–7. Swammerdamella spinigera sp. nov. (♂, holotype). 1. Wing, scale bar: 0.5 mm. 2. Spiracular sclerite, scale bar: 0.05 mm. 3. Tergite 6, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 4. Tip of abdomen in lateral view, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 5. Segment 7 (sternite above), scale bar: 0.1 mm. 6. Genital capsule in ventral view, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 7. Sperm pump, scale bar: 0.1 mm." pageId="6" pageNumber="446">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
) bearing a pair of elongate acute projections posteriorly; genital capsule with hardly developed lateral projections, yellowish apical lobes densely beset with short spinulae, and heavily sclerotized aedeagal plate and aedeagal complex (
<figureCitation id="51AF9DCDFFC7FF9DFAF8FEF79ED3DC7D" box="[1312,1421,268,294]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–7" captionStartId="6.[151,270,1894,1918]" captionTargetBox="[171,1426,688,1887]" captionTargetId="figure-272@6.[151,1436,683,1893]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 1–7. Swammerdamella spinigera sp. nov. (♂, holotype). 1. Wing, scale bar: 0.5 mm. 2. Spiracular sclerite, scale bar: 0.05 mm. 3. Tergite 6, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 4. Tip of abdomen in lateral view, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 5. Segment 7 (sternite above), scale bar: 0.1 mm. 6. Genital capsule in ventral view, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 7. Sperm pump, scale bar: 0.1 mm." pageId="6" pageNumber="446">Figs 4, 6</figureCitation>
). Sperm pump as in 
<figureCitation id="51AF9DCDFFC7FF9DFEAAFEC99AE7DC17" box="[370,441,306,332]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–7" captionStartId="6.[151,270,1894,1918]" captionTargetBox="[171,1426,688,1887]" captionTargetId="figure-272@6.[151,1436,683,1893]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 1–7. Swammerdamella spinigera sp. nov. (♂, holotype). 1. Wing, scale bar: 0.5 mm. 2. Spiracular sclerite, scale bar: 0.05 mm. 3. Tergite 6, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 4. Tip of abdomen in lateral view, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 5. Segment 7 (sternite above), scale bar: 0.1 mm. 6. Genital capsule in ventral view, scale bar: 0.1 mm. 7. Sperm pump, scale bar: 0.1 mm." pageId="6" pageNumber="446">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C92B8148FFC7FF9DFF1EFEA29E3BDF55" blockId="6.[151,1436,152,642]" pageId="6" pageNumber="446">
Female. 1.6 mm long. Wing 1.7 mm long. As male in general colour and morphology except antennae, less clavate apically. Genitalia. Tergite 8 short, incised posteriorly to accommodate the cerci (
<figureCitation id="51AF9DCDFFC7FF9DFB27FE7B9E16DCC1" box="[1279,1352,384,410]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–9" captionStartId="7.[151,271,735,759]" captionTargetBox="[156,1430,198,709]" captionTargetId="figure-420@7.[151,1436,194,710]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 8–9. Swammerdamella spinigera sp. nov. (♀, paratype, sa Duchessa), scale bar: 0.1 mm. 8. Terminalia in dorsal view. 9. Terminalia in ventral view." pageId="6" pageNumber="446">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
); cerci separated on all their length, covered with minute spinose setulae on entire surface and with usual setulae along apical margin only (
<figureCitation id="51AF9DCDFFC7FF9DFE08FE369946DCBC" box="[464,536,461,487]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–9" captionStartId="7.[151,271,735,759]" captionTargetBox="[156,1430,198,709]" captionTargetId="figure-420@7.[151,1436,194,710]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 8–9. Swammerdamella spinigera sp. nov. (♀, paratype, sa Duchessa), scale bar: 0.1 mm. 8. Terminalia in dorsal view. 9. Terminalia in ventral view." pageId="6" pageNumber="446">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
); tergite 9 produced posteriorly into 2 lateral lobes encompassing the cerci; sternite 8 more strongly sclerotized on undulated anterior margin, weakly sclerotized posteriorly (
<figureCitation id="51AF9DCDFFC7FF9DFAD7FE0F9E09DF55" box="[1295,1367,500,526]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–9" captionStartId="7.[151,271,735,759]" captionTargetBox="[156,1430,198,709]" captionTargetId="figure-420@7.[151,1436,194,710]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 8–9. Swammerdamella spinigera sp. nov. (♀, paratype, sa Duchessa), scale bar: 0.1 mm. 8. Terminalia in dorsal view. 9. Terminalia in ventral view." pageId="6" pageNumber="446">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="818ED2C3FFC7FF9CFF1EFDE198EDDEC0" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="447" pageId="6" pageNumber="446" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="C92B8148FFC7FF9DFF1EFDE19A75DFD9" blockId="6.[151,1436,152,642]" pageId="6" pageNumber="446">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC7FF9DFF1EFDE19A0DDF6F" bold="true" box="[198,339,538,564]" pageId="6" pageNumber="446">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name 
<taxonomicName id="0E94FACBFFC7FF9DFE39FDE1990EDF68" authorityName="Haenni" authorityYear="2009" box="[481,592,538,563]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Swammerdamella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="446" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinigera">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC7FF9DFE39FDE1990EDF68" box="[481,592,538,563]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="446">spinigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a feminine adjective meaning ‘bearing spines’, refers to the unusual spinulation of the ventral lobes of the genital capsule and the acute projections of tergite 7 of the male of the new species.
</paragraph>
<caption id="9DEBD1C0FFC7FF9DFF4FF89D9B96DAB1" pageId="6" pageNumber="446" startId="6.[151,270,1894,1918]" targetBox="[171,1426,688,1887]" targetPageId="6">
