<paragraph id="C92B8148FFC6FF9CFF2DFCAD98DEDE28" blockId="7.[151,1436,854,1112]" box="[245,896,854,883]" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC6FF9CFF2DFCAD9AD1DE28" bold="true" box="[245,399,854,883]" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">Chorotype.</emphasis>
A possible W-Mediterranean element.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C92B8148FFC6FF9CFF1FFC8498EDDEC0" blockId="7.[151,1436,854,1112]" box="[199,947,895,924]" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC6FF9CFF1FFC849A8DDEC7" bold="true" box="[199,467,895,924]" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">Italian distribution.</emphasis>
Presently only known from 
<collectingRegion id="0B504FAAFFC6FF9CFC98FC8498F1DEC0" box="[832,943,895,923]" country="Italy" name="Sardegna" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">Sardinia</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="818ED2C3FFC6FF9CFF1FFC5C9E4FD903" pageId="7" pageNumber="447" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="C92B8148FFC6FF9CFF1FFC5C9A94DE9F" blockId="7.[151,1436,854,1112]" box="[199,458,935,964]" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC6FF9CFF1FFC5C9A62DE9F" bold="true" box="[199,316,935,964]" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">Ecology.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C92B8148FFC6FF9CFF1EFC329E4FD903" blockId="7.[151,1436,854,1112]" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC6FF9CFF1EFC329A4DDEB8" bold="true" box="[198,275,969,995]" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">Notes.</emphasis>
This species and the preceding one both belong to the 
<taxonomicName id="0E94FACBFFC6FF9CFC2FFC319FC6DEB8" baseAuthorityName="Duda" baseAuthorityYear="1928" box="[1015,1176,970,995]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Swammerdamella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="447" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pediculata">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC6FF9CFC2FFC319FC6DEB8" box="[1015,1176,970,995]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">S. pediculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group of species of 
<taxonomicName id="0E94FACBFFC6FF9CFF4FFC0A9A32D951" box="[151,364,1009,1034]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Swammerdamella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="447" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC6FF9CFF4FFC0A9A32D951" box="[151,364,1009,1034]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">Swammerdamella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which are characterized by the 8-segmented flagellomere of antennae, the elongated M fork about as long as M stem, and by the genital structures. Besides the Palaearctic 
<taxonomicName id="0E94FACBFFC6FF9CFBACFBEC9E37D96A" authority="(Duda)" baseAuthorityName="Duda" baseAuthorityYear="1928" box="[1140,1385,1047,1073]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Swammerdamella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="447" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pediculata">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC6FF9CFBACFBEC9E51D96B" box="[1140,1295,1047,1072]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">S. pediculata</emphasis>
(Duda)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="0E94FACBFFC6FF9CFF4FFBC59A2AD903" authority="Cook" authorityName="Cook" authorityYear="1972" box="[151,372,1086,1112]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Swammerdamella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="447" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="genypodis">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC6FF9CFF4FFBC59A75D90C" box="[151,299,1086,1111]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">S. genypodis</emphasis>
Cook
</taxonomicName>
, the group also includes the Nearctic 
<taxonomicName id="0E94FACBFFC6FF9CFCF4FBC59F4ED903" authority="(Loew)" baseAuthorityName="Loew" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[812,1040,1086,1112]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Swammerdamella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="447" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pygmaea">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC6FF9CFCF4FBC598EDD90C" box="[812,947,1086,1111]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">S. pygmaea</emphasis>
(Loew)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="0E94FACBFFC6FF9CFB92FBC59E4FD903" authority="Cook." authorityName="Cook." box="[1098,1297,1086,1112]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Swammerdamella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="447" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="confusa">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC6FF9CFB92FBC59F9CD90C" box="[1098,1218,1086,1111]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">S. confusa</emphasis>
Cook.
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="818ED2C3FFC6FF93FF4FFB439BADDD83" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="448" pageId="7" pageNumber="447" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="C92B8148FFC6FF9CFF4FFB439A79D98E" blockId="7.[151,295,1208,1237]" box="[151,295,1208,1237]" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC6FF9CFF4FFB439A79D98E" bold="true" box="[151,295,1208,1237]" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">Discussion</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C92B8148FFC6FF9CFF4FFAFA9A78DB9F" blockId="7.[151,1436,1281,2003]" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">
The present material includes 11 species and thus represents a very significant increase of our knowledge of Sardinian 
<taxonomicName id="0E94FACBFFC6FF9CFED7FAD39AC0D819" box="[271,414,1320,1346]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="447" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Scatopsidae</taxonomicName>
, which was extremely poor until now. Indeed, no less than 10 species are new records for the island. Little less than half of them are widespread taxa: 
<taxonomicName id="0E94FACBFFC6FF9CFC44FAB49F2AD833" baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1830" box="[924,1140,1359,1384]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Coboldia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="447" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscipes">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC6FF9CFC44FAB49F2AD833" box="[924,1140,1359,1384]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">Coboldia fuscipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="0E94FACBFFC6FF9CFB68FAB49E31D833" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[1200,1391,1359,1384]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Scatopse" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="447" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="notata">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC6FF9CFB68FAB49E31D833" box="[1200,1391,1359,1384]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">Scatopse notata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are cosmopolitan, while 
<taxonomicName id="0E94FACBFFC6FF9CFE57FA8E99EED8D5" baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1818" box="[399,688,1397,1422]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Apiloscatopse" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="447" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavicollis">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC6FF9CFE57FA8E99EED8D5" box="[399,688,1397,1422]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">Apiloscatopse flavicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="0E94FACBFFC6FF9CFD19FA8E988BD8D5" baseAuthorityName="Zetterstedt" baseAuthorityYear="1850" box="[705,981,1397,1422]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Reichertella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="447" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="geniculata">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC6FF9CFD19FA8E988BD8D5" box="[705,981,1397,1422]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">Reichertella geniculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="0E94FACBFFC6FF9CFBC8FA8E9E2ED8D5" baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1830" box="[1040,1392,1397,1422]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Swammerdamella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="447" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevicornis">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC6FF9CFBC8FA8E9E2ED8D5" box="[1040,1392,1397,1422]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">Swammerdamella brevicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are common European (or W-Palaearctic for the latter) species with a wide distribution. It is more difficult to discuss the other taxa, as several of them have been recognized only recently and their distribution is still insufficiently known. 
<taxonomicName id="0E94FACBFFC6FF9CFE46FA129998DB59" authorityName="Haenni &amp; Godfrey" authorityYear="2009" box="[414,710,1513,1538]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Rhegmoclemina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="447" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lunensis">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC6FF9CFE46FA129998DB59" box="[414,710,1513,1538]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">Rhegmoclemina lunensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, known elsewhere only from 
<collectingCountry id="B183C1D8FFC6FF9CFBF5FA129FCDDB58" box="[1069,1171,1513,1539]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">England</collectingCountry>
, may be an up to now overlooked European element. The Mediterranean component is represented by at least 2 species, namely the new 
<taxonomicName id="0E94FACBFFC6FF9CFF17F9CC9AF3DB0B" authority="Enderlein" authorityName="Enderlein" box="[207,429,1590,1616]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Rhexoza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="447" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC6FF9CFF17F9CC9A6CDB0B" box="[207,306,1591,1616]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">Rhexoza</emphasis>
Enderlein
</taxonomicName>
and the new 
<taxonomicName id="0E94FACBFFC6FF9CFD93F9CC98C6DB0B" authority="Enderlein" authorityName="Enderlein" box="[587,920,1590,1616]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Swammerdamella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="447" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC6FF9CFD93F9CC9842DB0B" box="[587,796,1591,1616]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">Swammerdamella</emphasis>
Enderlein
</taxonomicName>
, that are otherwise known only from 
<collectingCountry id="B183C1D8FFC6FF9CFA8AF9CD9EC6DB0B" box="[1362,1432,1590,1616]" name="Spain" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">Spain</collectingCountry>
. Three taxa, 
<taxonomicName id="0E94FACBFFC6FF9CFEF0F9A69AAADB2C" box="[296,500,1629,1655]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Colobostema" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="447" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC6FF9CFEF0F9A69A99DB2D" box="[296,455,1629,1654]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">Colobostema</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="0E94FACBFFC6FF9CFDDBF9A6980ADB2D" authority="Haenni, 2009" authorityName="Haenni" authorityYear="2009" box="[515,852,1629,1654]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Swammerdamella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="447" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinigera" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC6FF9CFDDBF9A6980ADB2D" box="[515,852,1629,1654]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">Swammerdamella spinigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="E0D3E021FFC6FF9CFC85F9A698E5DB2C" box="[861,955,1629,1655]" pageId="7" pageNumber="447" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and the 
<taxonomicName id="0E94FACBFFC6FF9CFBFDF9A69E5DDB2C" box="[1061,1283,1629,1655]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Anapausis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="447" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="FBE05D5AFFC6FF9CFBFDF9A69FFCDB2D" box="[1061,1186,1629,1654]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">Anapausis</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
are possible endemic Sardinian species, although they may well also represent Mediterranean elements with a wider distribution.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C92B8148FFC6FF93FF1EF92A9BADDD83" blockId="7.[151,1436,1281,2003]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1436,152,216]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="448" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">
Even if based upon a single survey of a limited region only, the fauna of 
<taxonomicName id="0E94FACBFFC6FF9CFBFDF92A9FEFDBB0" box="[1061,1201,1745,1771]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="447" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Scatopsidae</taxonomicName>
of Sardinia appears nevertheless to present a very interesting and original assemblage of species. It should however be noticed that the occurrence of several other scatopsid species may be expected on the island. This also highlights the very poor state of our general knowledge of the family in the Mediterranean region. Indeed, Sardinia, with 11 recorded taxa, appears to be much better known when compared with other large islands, e.g. 
<collectingCountry id="B183C1D8FFC6FF9CFAC5F8979E27DADD" box="[1309,1401,1900,1926]" name="France" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">Corsica</collectingCountry>
(5 species), 
<collectingRegion id="0B504FAAFFC6FF9CFEDDF8699A14DAF7" box="[261,330,1938,1964]" country="Italy" name="Sicilia" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">Sicily</collectingRegion>
(2 species) or Crete (2 species) (
<bibRefCitation id="AD05FCB9FFC6FF9CFD0AF8699821DAF7" author="Haenni, J. - P." box="[722,895,1938,1964]" pageId="7" pageNumber="447" refId="ref5772" refString="Haenni, J. - P. (2004 b) Fauna Europaea: Scatopsidae. In: De Jong, H. (Ed.), Fauna Europaea: Diptera Nematocera. Fauna Europaea version 1.1, available at http: // www. faunaeur. org [accessed September 2009 as version 1.3 of April 19 th 2007.]" type="url" year="2004">Haenni 2004b</bibRefCitation>
). In this respect, the fauna of 
<collectingCountry id="B183C1D8FFC6FF9CFB38F8699E48DAF7" box="[1248,1302,1938,1964]" name="Italy" pageId="7" pageNumber="447">Italy</collectingCountry>
as a whole remains extremely poorly known since only 16 species of 
<taxonomicName id="0E94FACBFFC6FF9CFCBEF84298A9DA88" box="[870,1015,1977,2003]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="447" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Scatopsidae</taxonomicName>
had been recorded until now. The present survey brings this number to 21, which is probably only one third of the real number of expected species.
</paragraph>
